Good news - aging isn’t quite the horror story movies told us it is. 

Fuck walking - I’m sprinting into 38. 

I wanted to leave you with some of my well earned wisdom:
1. Get in photos - this is all so fleeting. 
2. Say yes to opportunities. 
3. Laugh more. 
4. Find someone to share your life with that let’s you be yourself. In every way. 
5. Get the Botox. 
6. Appreciate everything. 
7. Always find the good, even in hard days. 
8. Do not sacrifice your values for anything. 
9. Book a dentist appt and floss your teeth. We only have one set. 
10. Write your positive mantra everywhere, so you read it again and again.

✨Lucky girl energy ✨

The other day a friend asked me about my 2023 mantra, “I’m so lucky, everything works out for me.” A viral tiktok trend I happened upon just before rage deleting the app that was a massive drain on my time and brainpower. 

Engaging with this person about the words I’ve embraced this year helped my brain understand my real thoughts on it. It has nothing to do with luck, and everything to do with gratitude. 

When good things happen, I speak my mantra. When not so good things happen, I speak it even harder. It’s written on my mirror, so when work days get tough, I remember to say it. My closest friends are also speaking it, so they remind me regularly. 

I enter each day finding gratitude wherever possible, and acknowledging that even when things aren’t ideal, they’re still pretty damn great and I am thankful to be where I am; with the people I’m with; working where I’m working. 

My close second mantra always and forever is, everyday above ground is a good day. 

I hope you have a good day ❤️

 #people #energy #gratitude #positivemindset 
(Photo by my 6 year old son, who is my everyday reminder that I really am so lucky)

Tell me, how do you make friends as an adult?

Making friends in 2023 is a little different than when I was younger. It’s also one of the most frequent questions I get in my stories. How to make adult friends. 

Here is my one and only suggestion: 

Be bold. 

Connect with people - build relationships. Ask for what you want. I have wanted to meet @kirstenwendlandt for a while. I love her vibe and energy. She’s massively talented, incredibly beautiful, and fun to chat with. What I didn’t know was how funny she is. 

The only secret to making adult friends is boldness and bravery. 

Maybe a bit of fucking luck.

I’ve always rolled my eyes at people who announce their departure from social media - short or long term. I promised myself when I was ready to leave, I’d leave. 
Then I grew a community of people I am blessed to know, one that cares. I deactivated this account the other day and the messages flooded in through other avenues. Facebook (since been deactivated as well), LinkedIn, text, email and through friends. 
I realized it’s completely unfair of me to just vanish after years of connecting and building genuine relationships. 

“Bottom line is, even if you see 'em coming, you're not ready for the big moments. No one asks for their life to change, not really. But it does. So what are we, helpless? Puppets? No. The big moments are gonna come. You can't help that. It's what you do afterwards that counts. That's when you find out who you are.” 

I don’t know how long this will be - In this moment, I think it’ll be forever. If not permanent, I know it has to change. The conundrum is that I don’t know how to change - I also don’t know how to exist here the way I have. 

It’s all riddles and I don’t intend it to be. In a nutshell, I received some feedback from someone whose opinion matters and that feedback has me calling into question a lot about myself - how I show up on the internet. Something that until recently, I was very confident in. 

So, with that, let me start with a heartfelt apology. To everyone and no one. To anyone who’s ever been impacted negatively by something I’ve said, an opinion I’ve shared. 

Thank you to those who have put faith and trust in me over the years. I realized very early in my social media journey I wanted to be the good i felt was missing in a lot of social media. I found a good group of people who resonated with that. If we’ve ever exchanged a single message, if you’ve ever clicked a link I’ve shared, ordered monat, supported my friends - thank you. 

xoxo 
Meg 

Ps, for monat vip needs, see the link in my bio. 
Pss, brownie points for anyone who knows where that quote is from

Anyone else not fall instantly in love with your baby? 

Maybe moms aren’t supposed to admit that - but after 20 hours of hard labour with Ivy, I looked at him and thought, “oh… ok”. 

I was proud of myself. Excited it was over. But that overwhelming how did I live without you feeling? Nope. 

I felt kinda trash about it tbh. Then about 7-10 days later; I was sitting in bed with him in my lap. Staring at his sweet face - and it hit me. I would do anything. Be anything. Whatever he needed. That rushing undeniable sense of love and connection was finally there - and it’s only grown since. 

I have an ocean of pregnancy announcements on my feed - I wanted to share because I felt broken in the first few days with him. Why didn’t I cry when he was born? Why didn’t I feel like my whole world had shifted? Be gentle with yourself - giving birth is like a beautiful train wreck. Sometimes you gotta let the shock and awe wear off before you can really feel it.

All is clear. If you have a family history of breast cancer - get screened.
